Slaves were not officially freed in Nigeria until 1943,25 which perpetuates the socially enforced need for abortion due to financial restraints, societal taboos, and cultural disconnect from the sacredness of life.26 As of 2013, fetal homicide laws under the Shipping (Amendment) Act 1969 only allowed prosecution if the fetus was born alive but then miscarried.27 Though human rights activists have petitioned the Federal Government to alter the laws, there is no conclusive indication that they will officially change at this time.28 In contrast to abortion, human rights activists view government support for contraception to be much more controversial. One study reported 72% of Nigerians who were cognizant of the limited availability of government contraceptive assistance would be more willing to use birth control if provided by government funds.29 This is due, in large part, to a lack of education on family planning methods and the fear that birth control methods have the side effect of contraceptive pills.30 However, over 94% of the subjects in the study reported that they were unaware that family planning prevented diseases related to reproduction and 95% also did not realize that family planning prevents sexually transmitted infections.31 Consequently, there is no federal policy on family planning that could be utilized as a model; each state determines its own practices and coverage based on legal challenges from women’s rights activists and the government’s funding capacity.32 23.
